Okay, let's break this down. We need to create an AWS IAM role with a specific name and trust relationship, and then attach a managed policy to it. Here's the plan:

1.  **`aws_iam_role` resource:** This will create the IAM role itself. We'll set the `name` to "eks-fargate-profile-example".
2.  **`assume_role_policy`:** This part of the `aws_iam_role` resource will define the trust relationship. It needs to allow the `eks-fargate-pods.amazonaws.com` service to assume this role. This will be expressed as a JSON document.
3.  **`aws_iam_role_policy_attachment` resource:** We'll use this to attach the `arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AmazonEKSFargatePodExecutionRole` managed policy to the newly created role.

```hcl
resource "aws_iam_role" "fargate_profile_example" {
  name               = "eks-fargate-profile-example"
  assume_role_policy = jsonencode({
    Version = "2012-10-17"
    Statement = [
      {
        Action = "sts:AssumeRole"
        Effect = "Allow"
        Principal = {
          Service = "eks-fargate-pods.amazonaws.com"
        }
      },
    ]
  })
}

resource "aws_iam_role_policy_attachment" "fargate_profile_example_attachment" {
  role       = aws_iam_role.fargate_profile_example.name
  policy_arn = "arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AmazonEKSFargatePodExecutionRole"
